                <%= image_tag url_for(@card_1.image), :class => "card-img-top", :theme => "thumb" %>
                <div class="card-body">
                  <p class="card-text">The big project I worked on was an EDI Mapping Portal Service using VB 5, then C++ and eventually C#. Clients would use our web-based service to do their X12 mapping translations for the transmission of electronic data between to different legacy systems in a scified protocol. We positioned outrselves into being a SaaS provider and you can still read the old press releases as well as look through the old documentation. The project started off as a VB5 app running on 2 large DEC Alpha servers with NT Server running IIS. We also managed the internal network of offices and all the internal and external support and service calls. We built ourselves an Astrix based PBX phone system and integrated that into our network as well. Occasionally we had local clients and serviced them with other developmental needs. A client needed to migrate from using Novell Netware 5 to NT Server Platform and I did that as well as a lot of work on their shared Microsoft Access database which managed the entire company I think. it was a database built like an desktop application. Thanks Form Wizard. . Besides that we did other fn projects like integrate a UMich Directory server for which I wrote the server side API service and another employee built the client plug in for our windows NT machines so we could have a centralized directory to authenticate to. This is common practice now and every one does it. But back then you authentecated to a domain and it was an entire diffrent beast. We wrote scripts and helpers, wherever needed, so it because our all-in-one authenticator. A year or so later Microsoft announced they too had a directory server. Netscape used it first commercially for their browser product but I came up with the Authentication Server because we had a legacy Unix authentication system and a seperate Windows based one. Built it all from scratch in C and C++ back then, now it's a plugin and you use OMNIAuth or something similar. But back in 1999 or whatever year that was, I think we were the only ones doing it. I left the company for a few years to pursue some classes at the University and start a family</p>
                  <div class="d-flex justify-content-between align-items-center">
                    <div class="btn-group">
                      <a href="https://www.rtsz.com"><button type="button" class="btn btn-sm btn-outline-secondary">Research Triangle Software</button></a>
                    </div>
                    <small class="text-muted"></small>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="col-md-4">
