                <%= image_tag url_for(@card_2.image), :class => "card-img-top", :theme => "thumb" %>
                <div class="card-body">
                  <p class="card-text" color="white">When I returned a few years later I worked on a large scale email branding service utilizing a custom built Microsoft Outlook API plug-in to manipulate out-going mail to ensure a consistant look and feel went out with each email. They are still using the same system I worked on from almost 10 years ago. Complete with the same home page including the <a href="http://www.lettermark.com/LetterMark-encryption-feature.htm" />Lettermark Encryption option for MS Outlook</a> We also developed our own custom suite of portable applications and a stand alone encryption product as well. You can see those things and poke around in the support wiki and see more about what I did there. Many people worked to build the lettermark system before I was there but the portable security suite and the encryption addon were mainly developed by myself and one other developer. The entire suite of applications were registered and updated via an Active-X plugin we built our own license applications and used the <a href="https://webupdate.rtsz.com">webupdate system</a> to validate ownership of the device buy generating a device specific license-key to prevent piracy and validate authenticity of the produc. It was pretty fancy for it's day. The order of events were to log-in to the webserver, pick your device from those our activex plug-in detected on your system, transfer the hardware information to our system, validate the license and then provide any updates automatically to the USB device directly on your computer's USB device. At the time 512 MB USB devices were all the rage. We sold quite thousands of them. You can see some of my Letermark work still in the <a href="http://support.rtsz.com/mw/index.php?limit=100&tagfilter=&title=Special%3AContributions&contribs=user&target=dhopkins%40rtsz.com&namespace=&associated=1&year=&month=-1">logs</a> from a long time ago as well as remnants of the documentation for Lettermark, the Cryptolock software and Portable Security Suite</p>
